>>> [ 13] 3.2
    [ 14] Pantograph Control
>>> [ 15] 3.2.1
    [ 16] Pantograph - Lifting
>>> [ 17] 3.2.1.1
    [ 18] Function Design
>>> [ 19] 3.2.1.1.1 Normal Condition
    [ 20] Lifting the pantograph is a precondition for collecting energy from catenary system.
    [ 21] Lifting can be performed automatically or manually. In any case, the driver selects a line voltage system (4-position
    [ 22] selector switch) and switches "raise pantograph 1" or "raise pantograph 2".
    [ 23] Country Code is needed to identify pantograph which is needed depending on country of operation.
    [ 24] The identified pantograph are lifted up on request.
    [ 25] TCMS sends to PCU by IP bus which type of pantograph has to be lifted. TCMS also commands 2 different DOs in
    [ 26] order to define which type of pantograph has to be lifted.
>>> [ 27] 3.2.1.1.2 Failure Condition
    [ 28] 1)
    [ 29] Pantograph doesn't lift up although an order was given.
    [ 30] 2)
    [ 31] Two pantographs of the selected type are lifting up. (unless for ice scraping)
    [ 32] 3)
    [ 33] Lifting of pantograph without order.
    [ 34] 4)
    [ 35] Wrong type of pantograph is lifting up.
    [ 36] 5)
    [ 37] Pantograph switch is in "up" position although related pantograph is lowered.
>>> [ 38] 3.2.1.1.3 Failure Supervision
    [ 39] 1)
    [ 40] If the pantograph is not raised after 35 seconds after the raise order and the main reservoir pressure is higher
    [ 41] than 750 kPa, the pantograph is considered faulty.
    [ 42] If no air pressure is detected at the pantograph 5 minutes after the raise order and the main reservoir pressure is
    [ 43] less than or equal to 750 kPa, the pantograph is considered faulty.
    [ 44] 2)
    [ 45] Both pantographs will be ordered down.
    [ 46] 3)
    [ 47] Pantograph will be lowered, considered faulty and blocked additionally an event will be set.
    [ 48] 4)
    [ 49] system detection detects invalid line voltage system or country code does not fit to raised pantograph. In both
    [ 50] cases all pantographs will be lowered and a failure message will be displayed.
    [ 51] 5)
    [ 52] TCMS ignores pantograph-switch and pantograph remains in lowered position. IDU indicates that switch has to
    [ 53] be turned to "down" position.
>>> [ 54] 3.2.1.2
    [ 55] Requirements
    [ 56] ID
>>> [ 57] 2F_04.01.Zefiro-Europe.TRS.619
    [ 58] Description
    [ 59] The following sequence shall be implemented:
    [ 60] * Driver selects the Country where the train is operated from the IDU.
    [ 61] * Driver selects the line voltage system
    [ 62] * The (not blocked or cut out) pantograph (one per 8 car train unit) for the chosen line voltage system shall be lifted
    [ 63] when requested by the driver
    [ 64] * Line voltage shall be detected and the chosen line voltage system verified
    [ 65] If the detection and verification are successful, the closing of line circuit breakers shall be enabled. ELSE a
    [ 66] diagnostic event shall be generated.
    [ 67] Safety level
    [ 68] N/A

